               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-278-person2301">
                  JOHN 
                  CHARLES HART
               <interp inst="t18320906-278-person2301" type="surname" value="CHARLES HART"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-278-person2301" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-278-person2301" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live with my father in <placeName id="t18320906-278-crimeloc1564">Vauxhall-bridge-road</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18320906-278-crimeloc1564" type="placeName" value="Vauxhall-bridge-road"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18320906-278-crimeloc1564" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320906-278-off1562 t18320906-278-crimeloc1564"></join>. On the 30th of July, in the afternoon, I saw the prisoner inside his shop in the act of secreting a pair of stays under her petticoats - she had not offered to buy any thing; I asked her what she was going to do with them - she denied having them, and dropped them at the same time: I am sure she was trying to conceal them, for I came into the shop about two minutes before, and watched her putting them under her petticoats; the handkerchiefs were not found till she was going to the station; when she had got three or four yards from our house they were found under her things - this shawl was found in her bosom at the station; they are all my father's - his name is Matthew.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. It is quite false that I went to put them under my clothes - I went to look at a pair of stays; there were two young women in the shop when I went in; and when he came to me, he said if I would give him 4s. for them, he would not take me. Witness. No I did not.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-278-person2302">
                  JOHN 
                  BASS
               <interp inst="t18320906-278-person2302" type="surname" value="BASS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-278-person2302" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-278-person2302" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             (Police-constable B 4). At half-past two o'clock, on the 30th of July, I went to the shop, and took the prisoner - when we had got a few yards from the shop, I saw what I thought was a handkerchief about the lower part of her legs; I looked, and found these two handkerchiefs; I took hold of them, and pulled them down - I took this blue shawl from her at the station, and this large knife was taken from her bosom.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner. As I was turning from the door these two handkerchiefs were outside, they were not in the shop.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-278-person2303">
                  JOHN 
                  CHARLES HART
               <interp inst="t18320906-278-person2303" type="surname" value="CHARLES HART"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-278-person2303" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-278-person2303" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I missed them from the side of the door.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. His sister came into the shop, and desired him not to take me - I offered 2s. 6d. for the stays, and he said he would have 4s., or he would prosecute me if it were only for his expences.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-278-person2304">
                  THOMAS 
                  GREENIN
               <interp inst="t18320906-278-person2304" type="surname" value="GREENIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-278-person2304" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-278-person2304" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I produce a certificate of the prisoner's former conviction, on the 31st of March, 1831, which I got from the clerk of the Westminster Session - I was present when she was convicted; she was imprisoned four months.</p>
